Each sample was shot three times, in different non-overlapping locations, for 300 seconds each time, at 40 kv, 8-25 microamps, through a filter (12 mil Al + 1 mil Ti + 6 mil Cu). Results were calibrated by first applying Speakman’s (3) OB40 method and then a lab specific calibration derived from international standards (AGV-2, B.C.R-2, BHVO-2, BIR-1a, DNC-1a, GSP-2, QLO-1, SRM-278, W-2a).

The instrument employs an X-ray tube with a Rh target and a 10-mm2 silicon drift detector with a typical resolution of 145 eV at 100,000 cps. All samples were analysed in an air path through a filter composed of 12 mil (304.8 μm) Al and 1 mil (25.4 μm) Ti (Bruker’s “yellow” filter), with an X-ray tube setting of 40 keV at 10.7 μA. The instrument was calibrated using Bruker’s S1CalProcess and a set of 24 international and University of Auckland Anthropology lab ‘‘in-house” rock standards BHVO-1, GSP-2, JA-1, JA-2, JA-3, JB-1a, JB-2 and JB-3.
